The '''National Rural Electric Cooperative Association''' ('''NRECA''') is the organization that represents the interests of over 900 [[Utility cooperative#Electric cooperatives|electric cooperative]]s in the [[United States of America|United States]], to various [[legislatures]]. Independent electric utilities are [[not-for-profit]] and are owned by their members. The Association, which was founded in 1942, unites the country's generation, transmission and distribution cooperatives which are found in 47 [[U.S. state|states]] and serve over 40 million people.<ref>{{cite book|last=Sherman|first=Howard J. [et al.]|title=Economics: An Introduction to Traditional and Progressive Views|year=2008|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|location=Armonk, N.Y.|isbn=978-0-7656-1668-5|pages=281–282|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KddU9UVMUcoC&lpg=PA281&ots=kmApc1Wyq7&dq=%22National%20Rural%20Electric%20Cooperative%20Association%22&pg=PA281#v=onepage&q=%22National%20Rural%20Electric%20Cooperative%20Association%22&f=false|edition=7th}}</ref> It is headquartered in [[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington, Virginia]].
Electric cooperatives serve 12 percent of the nation's population, yet own 42 percent of [[United States of America|America]]'s distribution lines, which covers three-quarters of the country. Currently, over 90% of electric cooperatives include [[renewable energy|renewable generation]] in their portfolios, receiving 11 percent of their total power from [[renewable energy|renewable sources]] compared to 8 percent for the entire utility sector.<ref>{{cite web|title=Renewable Energy|url=http://www.nreca.coop/nreca-on-the-issues/energy-operations/fuels/renewable-energy/|publisher=National Rural Electric Cooperative Association|accessdate=October 11, 2012}}</ref>
